Hi Margaret, Misty & all,
The manual radio sweep can produce some very clear messages. A few tips I
have found over the years. My best results were using a radio or stereo that
had very good quality of sound reproduction, typically with a large speaker
(over 6&#39;) or even larger external speakers. The ambiance of the room also
helps, try to record in a room with some space. Distance the recorder from
the sound source as far as practical. Don&#39;t overpower the recorder with loud
sound, experiment with different sound levels. Keep everyone else in the
house quiet during your sessions, easier said then done :). 

Currently I have been experimenting with light and sweeping heterodyne
sound. The method is much like a manual radio sweep except there is no radio
signals. The sweep &#39;noises&#39; are some how transformed to words we can hear.
This currenty requires a large tabletop full of test equipment to work. If I
can get the voices clearer I will attempt to downsize the method to
something the size of a table radio.
Here is an example I&#39;m attaching from a test session yesterday. I was about
to shut down the session. The second voice is my own.
Voice: &quot;We&#39;re talking on the tape&quot;
Dave: &quot;Thank you for testing with us good-bye&quot; 

They always refer to the recording process as &quot;tape&quot;, even though we have
moved on in technology.
Thanks for listening,
Retro-Dave


